\par 502.42b The permanent is sacrificed at the same time the spell is announced (see rule 409.1a). The total cost of the spell is reduced by the sacrificed permanent\rquote s mana cost (see rule 409.1f).
\par 
\par 502.42c Generic mana in the sacrificed permanent\rquote s mana cost reduces generic mana in the total cost to play the card with offering. Colored mana in the sacrificed permanent\rquote 
s mana cost reduces mana of the same color in the total cost to play the card with offering. Colored mana in the sacrificed permanent\rquote s mana cost that doesn\rquote 
t match colored mana in the colored mana cost of the card with offering, or is in excess of the card\rquote s colored mana cost, reduces that much generic mana in the total cost.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {502.43. Ninjutsu
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
502.43a Ninjutsu is an activated ability that functions only while the card with ninjutsu is in a player\rquote s hand. \'93Ninjutsu [cost]\'94 means \'93[Cost], Reveal this card from your hand, Return an unblocked creature you control to its owner
\rquote s hand: Put this card into play from your hand tapped and attacking.\'94
\par 
\par 502.43b The card with ninjutsu remains revealed from the time the ability is announced until the ability leaves the stack.
\par 
\par 502.43c A ninjutsu ability may be played only while a creature in play is unblocked. The creature with ninjutsu is put into play unblocked.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK4}
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {503. Copying Objects
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.1. Some objects create or become a \'93copy\'94 of a spell, permanent, or card. (Certain older cards were printed with the phrase \'93search for a copy.\'94 This section doesn\rquote 
t cover those cards, which have received new text in the Oracle card reference.)
\par 
\par 503.2. When copying an object, the copy acquires the copiable values of the original object\rquote 
s characteristics (name, mana cost, color, type, supertype, subtype, expansion symbol, rules text, power, and toughness) and, for an object on the stack, choices made when playing it (mode, targets, the value of X, whether a kicker cost was 
paid, how it will affect multiple targets, and so on). The \'93copiable values\'94
 are the values that are printed on the object, as modified by other copy effects, plus any values set for face-down spells or permanents. Other effects (including type-changing effects) and counters are not copied.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ Chimeric Staff is an artifact that reads \'93\{X\}
: Chimeric Staff becomes an X/X artifact creature until end of turn.\'94 Clone is a creature that reads, \'93As Clone comes into play, you may choose a creature in play. If you do, Clone comes into play as a copy of that creature.\'94
 After a Staff has become a 5/5 artifact creature, a Clone comes into play as a copy of it. The Clone is an artifact, not a 5/5 artifact creature. (The copy has the Staff\rquote s ability, however, and will become a creature if that ability is activated.)

\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.3. The copied information becomes the copiable values for the copy, replacing its previous copiable values. Objects that copy the object will use the new copiable values.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ Vesuvan Doppelganger reads, \'93
As Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play, you may choose a creature in play. If you do, Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of that creature except for its color and gains \lquote 
At the beginning of your upkeep, you may have this creature become a copy of target creature except for its color. If you do, this creature gains this ability.\rquote \'94
 A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Grizzly Bears (a 2/2 green creature with no abilities). Then a Clone comes into play as a copy of the Doppelganger. The Clone is a 2/2 blue Bear named Grizzly Bears that has the Doppelganger\rquote 
s upkeep-triggered ability.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.4. Some effects cause a permanent that\rquote s copying a permanent to copy a different permanent while remaining in play. The change doesn\rquote t trigger comes-into-play or leaves-play abilities. This also doesn\rquote 
t change any noncopy effects presently affecting the permanent.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ Unstable Shapeshifter reads, \'93Whenever a creature comes 
into play, Unstable Shapeshifter becomes a copy of that creature and gains this ability.\'94 A Shapeshifter is affected by Giant Growth, which reads \'93Target creature gets +3/+3 until end of turn.\'94
 If a creature comes into play later this turn, the Shapeshifter will become a copy of that creature, but it will still get +3/+3 from the Giant Growth.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.5. An object that comes into play \'93as a copy\'94 of another permanent becomes a copy as it comes into play. It doesn\rquote t come into play, and then become a copy of that permanent. If the text that\rquote 
s being copied includes any abilities that replace the comes-into-play event (such as \'93comes into play with\'94 or \'93as [this] comes into play\'94 abilities), those abilities will take effect. Also, any comes-into-play triggered abil
ities of the copy will have a chance to trigger.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ Skyshroud Behemoth reads, \'93
Fading 2 (This creature comes into play with two fade counters on it. At the beginning of your upkeep, remove a fade counter from it. If you can\rquote t, sacrifice it.) / Skyshroud Behemoth comes into play tapped.\'94
 A Clone that comes into play as a copy of a Skyshroud Behemoth will also come into play tapped with two fade counters on it.
\par }{\b Example:}{ Striped Bears reads, \'93When Striped Bears comes into play, draw a card.\'94 A Clone comes into play as a copy of Striped Bears. The Clone has the Bears\rquote  comes-into-play triggered ability, so the Clone\rquote 
s controller draws a card.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.6. When copying a permanent, any choices that have been made for that permanent aren\rquote t copied. Instead, if an object comes into play as a copy of another permanent, the object\rquote s controller will get to make any \'93as comes into play\'94
 choices for it.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{
 A Clone comes into play as a copy of Chameleon Spirit. Chameleon Spirit reads, in part, \'93As Chameleon Spirit comes into play, choose a color.\'94 The Clone won\rquote 
t copy the color choice of the Spirit; rather, the controller of the Clone will get to make a new choice.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.7. Because any choices that have been made for a permanent aren\rquote t copied, sometimes a copy card will gain an ability that refers to a choice that was never made. In that case, the choice is considered to be \'93zero\'94 or \'93undefined.\'94

\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{
 Voice of All comes into play and Unstable Shapeshifter copies it. Voice of All reads, in part, \'93As Voice of All comes into play, choose a color. / Voice of All has protection from the chosen color.\'94
 Unstable Shapeshifter never got a chance to choose a color, because it didn\rquote t come into play as a Voice of All card, so the Shapeshifter\rquote s protection ability doesn\rquote t protect it from anything at all.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.8. If an ability causes a player to make a choice as a copy comes into play, the copy will \'93remember\'94 that choice and continue to use it for its abilities if appropriate. If the choice is not appropriate, it is considered to be \'93zero\'94 or 
\'93undefined.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{
 A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Chameleon Spirit, and the Doppelganger\rquote s controller chooses blue. Later, the Doppelganger copies Quirion Elves. The Elves has the ability, \'93\{T\}: Add one mana of the chos
en color to your mana pool.\'94 If the mana ability of the Doppelganger is played, it will produce blue mana.
\par }{\b Example:}{ A Vesuvan Doppelganger comes into play as a copy of Caller of the Hunt. Caller of the Hunt reads, in part, \'93As Caller of the Hunt comes into play, choose a creature type.\'94 The Doppelganger\rquote 
s controller chooses Goblin. Later, the Doppelganger copies Quirion Elves. If the mana ability of the Doppelganger is played, it will fail to produce any mana. It won\rquote t produce Goblin mana.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.9. Some copy effects give an ability to the copy as part of the copying process. This ability becomes part of the copiable values for the copy, along with any other abilities that were copied. Also, some copy effects specifically state that they don
\rquote t copy certain characteristics; they retain their original values instead.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{
 Quirion Elves comes into play and an Unstable Shapeshifter copies it. The copiable values of the Shapeshifter now match those of the Elves, except that the Shapeshifter also has the ability \'93
Whenever a creature comes into play, Unstable Shapeshifter becomes a copy of that creature and gains this ability.\'94
 Then a Clone comes into play as a copy of the Unstable Shapeshifter. The Clone copies the new copiable values of the Shapeshifter, including the ability that the Shapeshifter gave itself when it copied the Elves.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.10. To copy a spell means to put a copy of the spell onto the stack; a copy of a spell isn\rquote t \'93played.\'94 In addition to copying the characteristics of the spell, all decisions mad
e when the spell was played are copied. These include mode, targets, the value of X, and optional additional costs such as buyback. (See rule 409, \'93Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\'94
) Choices that are normally made on resolution are not copied. A cop
y of a spell is itself a spell, but it has no spell card associated with it. It works just like a normal spell: it can be countered or it can resolve, and it uses the same timing rules as normal spells.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ A player plays Fork, targeting an Emerald Charm. Fork reads, \'93
Put a copy of target instant or sorcery spell onto the stack, except that it copies Fork\rquote s color and you may choose new targets for the copy.\'94 Emerald Charm reads, \'93Choose one \emdash 
 Untap target permanent; or destroy target global enchantment; or target creature loses flying until end of turn.\'94
 When the Fork resolves, it puts a copy of the Emerald Charm on the stack. The copy has the same mode that was chosen for the original Emerald Charm. It does not necessarily have the same target, but only because Fork allows choosing of new targets.

\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.10a A copy of a spell in a zone other than the stack ceases to exist. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 503.11. If an effect refers to a permanent by name, the effect still tracks that permanent even if it changes names or becomes a copy of something else.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ An Unstable Shapeshifter copies a Crazed Armodon. Crazed Armodon reads, \'93\{G\}
: Crazed Armodon gets +3/+0 and gains trample until end of turn. Destroy Crazed Armodon at end of turn. Play this ability only once each turn.\'94
 If this activated ability of the Shapeshifter is played, the Shapeshifter will be destroyed at end of turn, even if it\rquote s no longer a copy of Crazed Armodon at that time.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }{\cf1 503.12. An effect that instructs a player to \'93play a copy\'94 of an object follows the rules for playing spells and abilities, except that the copy is played while another spell or ability is resolving. Playing a copy 
of a nonland object follows steps 409.1a-409.1h of rule 409, \'93Playing Spells and Activated Abilities," then the copy becomes played. The played copy is a spell on the stack, and just like any other spell it can resolve or be countered.}{
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {504. Face-Down Spells and Permanents
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 504.1. One old card (Illusionary Mask) and the morph ability (see rule 502.26) allow spells and permanents to be face down.
\par 
\par 504.2. Face-down spells on the stack, face-down permanents in play, and face-down cards in the phased-out zone h
ave no characteristics other than those listed by the ability or rules that allow the card, spell, or permanent to be face down. Any listed characteristics are the copiable values of that object\rquote s characteristics. (See rule 418.5, \'93
Interaction of Continuous Effects,\'94 and rule 503, \'93Copying Objects.\'94) Objects that are put into play face down are turned face down before they come into play, so the permanent\rquote s comes-into-play abilities won\rquote 
t trigger (if triggered) or have any effect (if static). Objects that are played face down are turned face down before they are put onto the stack, so effects that care about the characteristics of a spell will see only the face-down spell\rquote 
s characteristics.
\par 
\par 504.3. You may look at a face-down spell you control on the stack or a face-down permanent you control at any time. You can\rquote 
t look at face-down cards in any other zone or face-down spells or permanents controlled by another player. The ability or rules that allow a permanent to be face down may also allow the permanent\rquote s 
controller to turn it face up. Spells normally can\rquote t be turned face up.
\par 
\par 504.4. If you control multiple face-down spells on the stack or face-down permanents in play, you must ensure at all times that your face-down spells and permanents can be easily diff
erentiated from each other. This includes, but is not limited to, knowing the order spells were played, the order that face-down permanents came into play, which creature attacked last turn, and any other differences between face-down spells or permanents
. Common methods for distinguishing between face-down objects include using counters or dice to mark the different objects, or clearly placing those objects in order on the table.
\par 
\par 504.5. As a face-down permanent is turned face up, its copiable values rever
t to its normal copiable values. Any effects that have been applied to the face-down permanent still apply to the face-up permanent. Any abilities relating to the permanent coming into play don\rquote t trigger and don\rquote 
t have any effect, because the permanent has already come into play.
\par 
\par 504.6. If a face-down permanent moves from the in-play zone to any zone other than the phased-out zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. If a phased-out face-down object moves to any zone other than t
he in-play zone, its owner must reveal it as he or she moves it. If a face-down spell moves from the stack to any zone other than the in-play zone, its owner must reveal it to all players as he or she moves it. At the end of each game, all face-down objec
ts in play, in the phased-out zone, or on the stack must be revealed to all players.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {505. Split Cards
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 505.1. Split cards have two card faces on a single card. The back of a split card is the normal }{\b Magic: The Gathering }{card back.
\par 
\par 505.2. In every zone except the stack, split cards have two sets of characteristics. As long as a split card is a spell on the stack, only the characteristics of the half being played exist. The other half\rquote 
s characteristics are treated as though they didn\rquote t exist.
\par 
\par 505.3. Because every split card consists of two halves with different colored mana symbols in their mana costs, each split card is a multicolored card except while it\rquote s a spell on the stack. While it\rquote s a spell on the stack, it\rquote 
s only the color of the half being played.
\par 
\par 505.4. Although split cards have two playable halves, each split card is only one card. For example, a player who has drawn or discarded a split card has drawn or discarded one card, not two.
\par 
\par 505.5. Effects that ask for a particular characteristic of a split card while it\rquote s in a zone other than the stack get an answer that consists of a combination of the split card\rquote s two halves.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ Infernal Genesis has an ability that reads, \'93At the beginning of each player
\rquote s upkeep, that player puts the top card from his or her library into his or her graveyard. He or she then puts X 1/1 black Minion creature tokens into play, where X is that card\rquote s converted mana cost.\'94
 If the top card of your library is Assault/Battery when this ability resolves, you get five 1/1 creature tokens because Assault\rquote s converted mana cost is 1 and Battery\rquote s is 4, for a total of 5.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 505.6. Effects that ask if a split card\rquote s characteristic (in any zone other than the stack) matches a given value get only one answer. This answer is \'93yes\'94 if either side of the split card matches the given value.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ Void reads, \'93
Choose a number. Destroy all artifacts and creatures with converted mana cost equal to that number. Then target player reveals his or her hand and discards all nonland cards with converted mana cost equal to the number.\'94
 If a player plays Void and chooses 1 or 4, his or her opponent would discard Assault/Battery. If the player chooses 5, Assault/Battery would be unaffected, because neither half has a converted mana cost of 5.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 505.7. If an effect instructs a player to name a card and the player wants to name a split card, the player must name both halves of the split card.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {506. Subgames
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 506.1. {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK19}Some cards allow players to play a }{\b Magic}{ subgame.{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK19} A \'93subgame\'94 is the game created by the card\rquote s effect. The \'93main game\'94
 is the game in which the spell or ability that created the subgame was played. The main game is suspended while the subgame is in progress. It resumes when the subgame ends.
\par 
\par 506.2. Any main-game abilities that trigger while the subgame is in progress aren\rquote t put onto the stack until the subgame is completed.
\par 
\par 506.3. To start the subgame, each player removes his or her library from the game face down. It becomes that player\rquote s deck in the subgame. Abilities that trigger on cards being removed from the main game face down will trigger.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {506.3a A player\rquote 
s deck in the subgame may have less than the minimum number of cards. If a player\rquote s deck contains less than seven cards, the player will lose the game as soon as it starts, even if he or she mulligans. (See rule 420, \'93State-Based Effects.\'94)

\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 506.4. The subgame proceeds like a normal game. Randomly determine which player goes first.
\par 
\par 506.5. All objects in the main game and all cards outside the main game are considered outside the subgame (except those specifically brought into the subgame).
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
506.5a Some effects can bring cards into a game from outside of it. Cards brought into a subgame from a main game are considered to
 be removed from the main game. Abilities in the main game that trigger on objects being removed from the main game will trigger.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 506.6. At the end of a subgame, each player puts all objects that were brought into the subgame into his or her library in the main game, then shuffles that library. Cards removed from the game in the subgame are not put into the player\rquote 
s main-game library. Instead they remain removed from the game in the main game.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ If a card was brought into the subgame either from the
 main game or from outside the main game, that card will be put into its owner\rquote s main-game library when the subgame ends.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 506.7. If another subgame is created during a subgame, there can be multiple subgames and main games. Each main game has one subgame, and each subgame has one main game. In this case, some games will be considered both a main game and a subgame at the sam
e time.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {507. Controlling Another Player\rquote s Turn
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {507.1. One card (Mindslaver) allows a player\rquote 
s turn to be controlled by another player. This effect applies to the next turn that the affected player actually takes. The entire turn is controlled; the effect doesn\rquote t end until the beginning of the next turn.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
507.1a Multiple turn-controlling effects that affect the same player overwrite each other. The last one to be created is the one that works.
\par 
\par 507.1b If a turn is skipped, any pending turn-controlling effects wait until the player who would be affected actually takes a turn.
\par 
\par 507.1c Only the control of the turn changes. All objects are controlled by their normal controllers.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 507.2. If information about an object would be visible to the player whose turn is controlled, it\rquote s visible to both that player and the controller of the turn.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ The controller of a player\rquote s turn can see that player\rquote 
s hand and the identity of any face-down creatures he or she controls.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 507.3. The controller of another player\rquote s tu
rn makes all choices and decisions that player is allowed to make or is told to make during that turn by the rules or by any objects. This includes choices and decisions about what to play, and choices and decisions called for by spells and abilities.

\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{
 The controller of the turn decides which spells to play and what those spells target, and makes any required decisions when those spells resolve.
\par }{\b Example:}{ The controller of the turn decides which of the player\rquote s creatures attack, and how those creatures assign their combat damage.
\par }{\b Example:}{ The controller of the turn decides which card the player chooses from outside the game with one of the }{\i0 Judgment\'99}{ Wishes. The player can\rquote t choose a card of the wrong type.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {507.3a The controller of another player\rquote s turn can use only that player\rquote 
s resources (cards, mana, and so on) to pay costs for that player.
\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{
 If the controller of the turn decides that the player will play a spell with an additional cost}{\i0  }{of discarding cards, the cards are discarded from the player\rquote s hand.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 507.3b The controller of another player\rquote s turn can\rquote t make that player concede. A player may concede the game at any time, even if his or her turn is controlled by another player. See rule 102.7.
\par 
\par 507.3c The controller of another player\rquote s turn can\rquote t make choices or decisions for that player that aren\rquote t called for by the rules, or by any objects. The controller also can\rquote 
t make any choices or decisions for the player that would be called for by the tournament rules.
\par }\pard\plain \s24\ql \li1500\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1500\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example: }{The player whose turn
 it is still chooses whether he or she leaves to visit the restroom, trades a card to someone else, takes an intentional draw, or calls a judge about an error or infraction.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 507.3d A player who controls another player\rquote s turn also continues to make his or her own choices and decisions.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 507.4. A player doesn\rquote t lose life due to mana burn while another player controls his or her turn. (Unused mana in players\rquote  mana pools is still lost when a phase ends. See rule 300.3.)
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {508. Flip Cards
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
508.1. Flip cards have a two-part card frame on a single card. The text that appears right side up on the card defines the card\rquote s normal characteristics. Additional alternative characteristics appear upside down on the card. The back of a fl
ip card is the normal }{\b Magic: The Gathering}{ card back.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {508.1a The top half of a flip card contains the card\rquote 
s normal name, text box, type line, power, and toughness. The text box usually contains an ability that causes the permanent to \'93flip\'94 if certain conditions are met.
\par 
\par 508.1b The bottom half of a flip card contains an alternative name, text box, type line, power, and toughness. These characteristics are used only if the permanent is in play and only if the permanent has been flipped.
\par 
\par 508.1c A flip card\rquote s color, mana cost, expansion symbol, illustration credit, and legal text don\rquote t change if the permanent has been flipped. Also, any changes to it by external effects will still apply.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 508.2. In every zone other than the in-play zone, and also in the in-
play zone before the permanent flips, a flip card has only the normal characteristics of the permanent. Once the flip permanent in the in-play zone has been flipped, the normal name, text box, type line, power, and toughness of the flip permanent don
\rquote t apply and the alternative versions of those characteristics apply instead.
\par }\pard\plain \s23\ql \li1200\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1200\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example: }{
Akki Lavarunner is a nonlegendary creature that flips into a legendary creature named Tok-Tok, Volcano Born. An effect that says \'93search for library for a legendary card\'94 can\rquote t find this flip card. An effect that says \'93
legendary creatures get +2/+2\'94 doesn\rquote t affect Akki Lavarunner, but it does affect Tok-Tok.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 508.3. If you control a flip permanent, you must ensure that it\rquote s clear at all times whether the permanent has flipped or not, both when it\rquote s untapped and when it\rquote 
s tapped. Common methods for distinguishing between flipped and unflipped permanents include using coins or dice to mark flipped objects.
\par 
\par 508.4. Flipping a permanent is a one-way process. Once a permanent has been flipped, it\rquote s impossible to flip the permanent back again. However, if flipped permanent leaves play, it forgets its previous existence.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {509. Ending the Turn
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
509.1. One card (Timestop) ends the turn when it resolves. When an effect ends the turn, follow these steps in order, as they differ from the normal process for resolving spells and abilities (see rule 413, \'93Resolving Spells and Abilities\'94).
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s21\ql \fi-300\li900\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin900\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
509.1a Remove every object on the stack from the game. Remove all attacking and blocking creatures, if any, from combat. All objects not in play or on the stack that aren\rquote 
t represented by cards will cease to exist the next time state-based effects are checked (see rule 420, \'93State-Based Effects).
\par 
\par 509.1b Check state-based effects. No player gets priority, and no triggered abilities are put onto the stack.
\par 
\par 509.1c The current phase and/or step ends. The game skips straight to the cleanup step. Skip any phases or steps between this phase or step and the cleanup step.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \fi-300\li600\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 509.2. No player gets priority during this process, so triggered abilities are not put onto the stack. If any triggered abilities have triggered between the spell or ability resolving and the cleanup step ending, there\rquote s a chance to play 
spells and abilities in the cleanup step. Then there will be another cleanup step before the turn finally ends. (see rule 314.3).
\par 
\par 509.3. Even though the turn ends, \'93at end of turn\'94 triggered abilities don\rquote t trigger because the end of turn step is skipped.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f4\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\page Glossary
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Ability
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\'93Ability\'94 and \'93effect\'94 are often confused with one another. An instruction in an object
\rquote s text is an ability. The result of following such an instruction is an effect. For more information, see section 4, \'93Spells, Abilities, and Effects.\'94
\par      When an activated ability is played, it goes onto the stack and stays there until it resolves or is countered.
\par      When an effect states that an object \'93gains\'94 or \'93has\'94 an ability, it\rquote s granting that object an ability. If an effect defines a property of an object (\'93[card or permanent] is [property]\'94), it\rquote 
s not granting an ability. For example, an enchant creature might read, \'93Enchanted creature is red.\'94 The enchantment isn\rquote t granting an ability of any kind; it\rquote s simply changing the enchanted creature\rquote s color to red.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Activated Ability
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {An activated ability is written as \'93activation cost: effect.\'94
 By paying the activation cost, a player may play such an ability whenever he or she has priority. See rule 403, \'93Activated Abilities.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Activation Cost
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {The activation cost of an activated ability is everything before the colon in \'93
activation cost: effect.\'94 It must be paid to play the ability. See rule 403, \'93Activated Abilities.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s28\ql \li400\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b Example:}{ The activation cost of an ability that reads \'93\{2\}, \{T\}: You gain 1 life\'94
 is two mana of any color plus tapping the permanent.
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Active Player
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
The active player is the player whose turn it is. The active player gets priority at the start of each phase or step (except for the untap and cleanup steps), after any spell or ability (
except a mana ability) resolves, and after combat damage resolves. See rule 200.3.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Active Player, Nonactive Player Order
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
Whenever both players are instructed to make choices at the same time, the active player makes all his or her choices first, then the nonactive player. This is called the \'93Active Player, Nonactive Player order\'94 rule, or \'93APNAP order\'94
 rule. See rule 103.4.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Additional Cost
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
Some spells have additional costs listed in their text. These are paid at the same time the player pays the spell\rquote s mana cost. See rule 409, \'93Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Affinity
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Affinity is a static ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. \'93Affinity [text]\'94
 means \'93This spell costs you \{1\} less to play for each [text] you control.\'94 The affinity ability only reduces generic mana costs. It doesn\rquote t reduce how much colored mana you have to pay for a spell. It can\rquote 
t reduce the cost to play a spell to less than 0. See rule 502.31, \'93Affinity.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Alternative Cost
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {The rules text of some spells reads, \'93You may [action] rather than pay [this object\rquote 
s] mana cost,\'94 or include the phrase, \'93you may play [this object] without paying its mana cost.\'94 These are alternative costs. Only one such alternative cost can be applied to any one spell. Other spells and abilities that ask for a spell\rquote 
s mana cost still see the actual mana cost, not what was paid to play the spell. If an effect requires paying additional costs to play a spell, it still applies to the alternative cost. See rule 409, \'93Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Amplify
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Amplify is a static ability. \'93Amplify X\'94 means \'93
As this object comes into play, reveal any number of cards from your hand that share a creature type with this object. This object comes into play with X +1/+1 counters on it for each card revealed this way. You can\rquote 
t reveal this card or any other cards that are coming into play at the same time as this card.\'94 See rule 502.27, \'93Amplify.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Ante (Obsolete)
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Earlier versions of the }{\b Magic}{ rules included an ante rule as a way of playing \'93for keeps.\'94
 Playing }{\b Magic}{ games for ante is now considered an optional variation on the game, and it is allowed only where it\rquote 
s not forbidden by law or by other rules. Playing for ante is strictly forbidden under DCI tournament rules. When using the ante rule
, each player puts one random card from his or her deck into his or her ante zone at the beginning of the game. At the end of the game, the winner becomes the owner of the cards in each player\rquote s ante zone. See rule 217.9, \'93Ante.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {APNAP Order
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {See Active Player, Nonactive Player Order.
\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Artifact
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
Artifact is a type. The active player can play artifacts only during his or her main phase when the stack is empty. When an artifact spell resolves, its controller puts it into play under his or her control. See rule 212.2, \'93Artifacts.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Artifact Creature
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {An artifact creature is a combination of artifact and creature, and it\rquote 
s subject to the rules for both. (See rule 212.2, \'93Artifacts.\'94) Some artifact creatures don\rquote t have a creature type. Those that do will say \'93Artifact Creature \emdash  [creature type]\'94; for example, \'93Artifact Creature \emdash  Golem.
\'94 \'93Artifact\'94 isn\rquote t a creature type.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Artifact Land
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {An artifact land is a combination of artifact and land, and it\rquote 
s subject to the rules for both. (See rule 212.2, \'93Artifacts.\'94) Artifact lands can only be played as lands. They can\rquote t be played as spells. Some artifact lands don\rquote t have a land type. Those that do will say \'93Artifact Land \emdash 
 [land type].\'94
