To declare attackers, the active player chooses a set of creatures that will attack and pays any costs they require to attack. Only creatures can attack, and the following creatures can\rquote 
t attack: tapped creatures (even those that can attack without tapping) and creatures the active player didn\rquote t control continuously since the beginning of the turn (except those
 with haste). Other effects may also affect whether or not a set of creatures could attack. See rule 500, \'93Legal Attacks and Blocks.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Declare Attackers Step
\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {The declare attackers step is the sec
ond step of the combat phase. The active player declares attackers during this step. Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. See rule 308, \'93Declare Attackers Step.\'94
